v.v.v.v.imp: 
.map(([name, score]) => ({ name, score }))
explain
Step-by-step Breakdown
🔹 Part 1 → .map()
map() loops through array and returns:

transformed array
🔹 Example
const arr = [1,2,3];
arr.map(x => x * 2);
returns:
[2,4,6]

🔹 In your case
Input array:
[
  ['manager', 40],
  ['developer', 10]
]
Each element is itself an array.

🔹 Part 2 → ([name, score])
This is:
array destructuring
🔹 Without destructuring
Normally you would write:
.map(emp => ({
   name: emp[0],
   score: emp[1]
}))
🔹 With destructuring
([name, score])
means:
const name = emp[0];
const score = emp[1];

automatically.
🔹 Example
Suppose current element is:
['manager', 40]
Then:
([name, score])
becomes:
name = 'manager'
score = 40

🔹 Part 3 → => ({ name, score })
This returns an object.
🔹 Why parentheses are needed
Arrow functions confuse:
object {}
with
function body {}
So this:
=> ({ name, score })
means:
return object

Without parentheses:
=> { name, score }
JavaScript thinks:
function body
and returns undefined.

🔹 Part 4 → { name, score }
This is:
object property shorthand
🔹 Equivalent long version
{
   name: name,
   score: score
}
🔹 Modern shorthand
{ name, score }

Cleaner ES6 syntax.
